## Why This Project Matters

well I would deploy on hugging face. compare my translation model to to other irish translation models. and same for the other languages. I will find a test dataset to evaluate all translation of models across languages and benchmark them.
How to benchmark smartly:
For Irish specifically, compare against:

Helsinki-NLP/opus-mt-ga-en on Hugging Face — this is the obvious baseline
Qomhrá if you can access it
Google Translate via their API (free tier is fine for a test set)

For Welsh, Helsinki-NLP has opus-mt models for cy-en too. For Breton and Scottish Gaelic coverage is thinner, which actually works in your favour — if you beat a sparse baseline on those languages, that's a meaningful result.

For the test dataset:

Flores-200 includes Irish and Welsh and is the standard low-resource MT benchmark — using it makes your results directly comparable to published papers
OPUS newstest splits if available for your language pairs
Tatoeba has held-out test splits you can use cleanly

Using Flores-200 in particular is a strong move — you can cite it properly and anyone in the field will immediately recognise it as a legitimate benchmark.
This sits at the intersection of low-resource NLP, multilingual LLMs, and computational linguistics. It builds on existing work but explores something that has not been clearly done: **training and analyzing a unified Celtic multilingual model**.
